          <h2>Brown Noise</h2>
          
    
      <p> 
      For individuals with ADHD who struggle with maintaining focus and productivity, 
      brown noise can create a more structured and calming atmosphere. By reducing 
      external stimuli, it can help enhance concentration and productivity during 
      tasks or work.
      The name “brown noise” comes from Robert Brown, who was a Scottish botanist. 
      He discovered something known as Brownian motion, which was the way that grains 
      of pollen in water move when looked at under a microscope. The idea is that brown 
      noise mimics these movements by using sound signals that change randomly and 
      produce static.
      
      
      A familiar example of brown noise is the sound of distant, rolling thunder.
       This type of noise aids mental focus and helps regulate sleep patterns in some individuals.
      
      The power density of brown noise decreases as the frequency increases, where power density
       is proportional to 1/f2. The rate of decrease is 6.02 dB per octave. Brown noise does not
      correspond to a power spectrum representing the color “brown.” Instead, it is a shortened
      form of Brownian motion or Brownian noise.
